Today was a comprehensive review session covering a wide range of fundamental topics in computing, Linux, networking, and virtualization.

Computer Components & Storage
Reviewed the motherboard as the central hub connecting all components.

Discussed different types of storage devices: HDDs (magnetic storage), SSDs (flash memory-based storage), and NVMe drives (high-speed PCIe storage).

Compare BIOS vs. UEFI boot systems and their impact on modern computing.

Examined the difference between 32-bit and 64-bit systems, focusing on RAM limitations and performance.

Explored different storage interfaces, including SCSI, SATA, and NVMe M.2.

Linux Essentials & System Administration
Practiced essential Linux terminal commands for navigation, file manipulation, and process management.

Compared different shell environments (Bash, Korn, Zsh, Fish).

Reviewed Linux user management, including standard vs. system users and permission structures.

Explored package management tools (APT for Debian-based systems and YUM/DNF for Red Hat-based systems).

Discussed software installation methods: source code compilation vs. precompiled binaries.

Networking Fundamentals
Reviewed the OSI and TCP/IP models, breaking down their respective layers.

Discussed networking hardware such as NICs, switches, routers, and access points.

Compared various networking cables (twisted pair, coaxial, fiber optic) and their use cases.

Examined the differences between IPv4 and IPv6, including address formatting and private vs. public IPs.

Walked through the DHCP process (DORA: Discover, Offer, Request, Acknowledge) and its role in network configuration.

Practiced network configuration commands on both Windows (ipconfig /all, nslookup) and Linux (ifconfig, ip a, nslookup, dig, host).

Virtualization
Discussed the role of virtualization in modern computing, including the differences between Type 1 (bare metal) and Type 2 (hosted) hypervisors.

Explored the benefits of virtualization: resource optimization, isolation, cost savings, and disaster recovery.
